      "description": "For Model Risk Level 5 Class III devices, hemolysis quantity-of-interest predictions must be confirmed by experimental-validation activities using physical bench or in-vitro test data. Simulation-only evidence is not sufficient to satisfy this requirement.",
      "requiredVerificationMethod": "experimental-validation"
    }
  ],
  "hasActivity": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/activity/mesh-refinement-simulation",
      "type": "Activity",
      "name": "High-fidelity mesh-refinement numerical simulation for hemolysis QoI",
      "description": "A systematic mesh-refinement study was conducted across four grid levels (coarse, medium, fine, extra-fine) using the Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis model. Inlet and outlet boundary conditions were prescribed from published FDA pump test conditions. The team argues that, because the boundary data are derived from physical experiments and the solver has been code-verified, this numerical simulation provides evidence equivalent to a direct experimental measurement of hemolysis. Richardson extrapolation was used to estimate the grid-converged hemolysis index, and Monte Carlo sampling was applied to propagate boundary-condition uncertainty. The resulting hemolysis index distribution was compared against the clinical threshold with a 95th-percentile margin.",
      "activityType": "numerical-simulation",
      "usedBoundaryDataFrom": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-pump-geometry-v3"
    }
  ],
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/hemolysis-qoi-result",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Hemolysis index validation result — mesh-refinement simulation",
      "description": "Richardson-extrapolated hemolysis index (NIH) = 0.0031 g/100 L at nominal operating point (5 L/min, 3000 rpm). Monte Carlo 95th-percentile NIH = 0.0047 g/100 L, below the clinical threshold of 0.010 g/100 L. The activity supporting this result is classified as a numerical-simulation; the narrative asserts this is 'as good as' experimental bench data because boundary conditions were sourced from physical test data, but no independent in-vitro hemolysis measurement was performed to directly corroborate the predicted NIH values.",
      "wasGeneratedBy": "https://uofa.net/synth/activity/mesh-refinement-simulation",
